<h2>3. Core Concept: Data Sources</h2>
<div class="important">
<strong>Critical Rule:</strong> Revenue & Leads come from OUR database, NOT from Facebook. Facebook only provides ad metrics.
</div>
<table>
<tr><th>Data</th><th>Source</th><th>How</th></tr>
<tr><td>Spend, Clicks, Impressions, Reach</td><td>Facebook API</td><td>Daily sync at 2 AM</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Revenue & Sales</strong></td><td><strong>Local Database</strong></td><td>Manual entry, Webhook, or API</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Leads</strong></td><td><strong>Local Database</strong></td><td>Manual entry, Webhook, or API</td></tr>
<tr><td>ROAS</td><td>Calculated</td><td>Revenue (local) ÷ Spend (Facebook)</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>4. Key Feature: Conversion API (CAPI) Integration</h2>
<div class="feature">
<strong>NEW:</strong> When a sale happens, we send the conversion data to Facebook via Conversion API. This helps Facebook optimize ad delivery for more conversions.
</div>
<p><strong>How it works:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Customer makes a purchase (received via webhook from payment gateway)</li>
<li>Sale is recorded in our dashboard with customer email, amount, country</li>
<li>Dashboard automatically sends this conversion event to Facebook CAPI</li>
<li>Facebook uses this data to optimize ads and show them to similar buyers</li>
<li>Dashboard reflects the sale in revenue metrics and ROAS calculations</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>CAPI Data Sent:</strong> Event name (Purchase), Event time, Customer email (hashed), Amount, Currency, Country, Transaction ID</p>

<h2>5. Dashboard Sections</h2>
<table>
<tr><th>Section</th><th>What it Shows</th></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Overview</strong></td><td>5 KPI cards (Spend, Revenue, ROAS, Leads, Pixel Status) + Quick snapshot (Today/Week/Month)</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Campaigns</strong></td><td>All campaigns with Status, Budget, Spend, Sales, Revenue, ROAS, Frequency, Clicks, Reach, Impressions</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Ad Sets</strong></td><td>Same metrics as Campaigns, grouped by parent campaign</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Ads</strong></td><td>Individual ads with creative preview + all metrics</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Country Performance</strong></td><td>Country-wise breakdown: Spend (Facebook) + Revenue (our data) + ROAS</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Sales by Ad Creative</strong></td><td>Each sale linked to the ad that generated it (Ad Name, Amount, Country, Date)</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>6. Smart Alerts (Key Differentiator)</h2>
<div class="highlight">
<strong>Why This Matters:</strong> Facebook doesn't tell you when to increase or decrease budget. Our alerts do.
</div>
<table>
<tr><th>Alert Type</th><th>Trigger</th><th>Recommended Action</th></tr>
<tr><td>Low ROAS</td><td>ROAS below 1.0 with spend > $100</td><td>Pause or optimize campaign</td></tr>
<tr><td>Zero Sales</td><td>No revenue but money being spent</td><td>Check landing page, offer</td></tr>
<tr><td>High Frequency</td><td>Same people seeing ad 3+ times</td><td>Refresh creative, expand audience</td></tr>
<tr><td>Overspend</td><td>Daily spend exceeds limit</td><td>Review budget settings</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>High ROAS (Scale Up)</strong></td><td>ROAS above 2.0</td><td><strong>Increase budget!</strong></td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Country Overspend</strong></td><td>Country spending but no sales</td><td><strong>Exclude or reduce in that country</strong></td></tr>
</table>

<h2>7. Country-Wise Tracking</h2>
<p>Shows which countries are <strong>profitable</strong> and which are <strong>wasting money</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Ad Spend per Country</strong> - From Facebook (synced daily)</li>
<li><strong>Revenue per Country</strong> - From our sales data (country_code field)</li>
<li><strong>ROAS per Country</strong> - Calculated to show profitability</li>
<li><strong>Alert if country spending but not converting</strong></li>
</ul>

